{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772554274,"nonce":"aL4SeB+gH0+kB2oSl2LiTZruZOc=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87vdlDa","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/335","origin":"github"},"title":"Design Makefile target taxonomy and dashboard concept","message":"## Context\n\nPart of #263 (Simplify scripts and Makefile interface). Emerged from brainstorming\nduring #325 (ADR-0007: Retain Make with dependency tracking).\n\nThe current Makefile has 19+ targets that grew organically. With the decision to adopt\nstamp-file dependencies (#332), the target surface area needs intentional design — not\njust adding stamps to existing targets, but rethinking what the user actually types and\nwhat should happen.\n\n## Current State\n\nThe workspace currently has these target categories:\n\n| Category | Targets | Count |\n|---|---|---|\n| Setup chain | `bootstrap`, `setup-core`, `setup-all`, `setup-underlay`, `setup-platforms`, `setup-sensors`, `setup-simulation`, `setup-ui` | 8 |\n| Core workflow | `build`, `test`, `clean` | 3 |\n| Status/info | `status`, `status-quick`, `validate`, `health-check` | 4 |\n| Dev tools | `setup-dev`, `format`, `lint` | 3 |\n| Agent container | `agent-build`, `agent-run`, `agent-shell`, `push-gateway` | 4 |\n| Maintenance | `sync`, `lock`, `unlock`, `revert-feature`, `pr-triage` | 5 |\n| Meta | `help`, `generate-skills` | 2 |\n\n## Proposed Target Tiers\n\n### Tier 1: Setup chain (stamp-based, mostly invisible)\n\nThese become internal Make dependencies, not user-facing targets:\n- `bootstrap` → `setup-dev` → `manifest` → per-layer setup → `build`\n- Dev tools (`pre-commit`, linters) are non-optional for workspace users — include in\n  the stamp chain rather than requiring a separate `make setup-dev`\n- Individual `setup-*` targets may remain as convenience entry points but are no longer\n  required knowledge\n\n### Tier 2: Developer workflow (explicit targets)\n\nWhat the user actually types:\n- `build`, `test`, `lint`, `clean` — core development cycle\n- `dashboard` — unified workspace status (see below)\n- `help` — self-documenting target list\n\n### Tier 3: Agent orchestration (explicit targets, evolving)\n\n- `agent-build`, `agent-run`, `agent-shell`, `push-gateway` — existing container targets\n- Future: `dispatch`, `agent-status` — toward coordinated multi-agent workflows\n\n## Dashboard Concept\n\nThe status/info targets (`status`, `status-quick`, `health-check`, `validate`) all\nanswer different slices of \"what's going on?\" but none answer the coordination question.\nA unified `dashboard` target could provide:\n\n- Active worktrees + their issue + branch + dirty/clean status\n- PR status per worktree (open, review state, CI status)\n- Stale worktrees (no recent activity, already-merged PRs)\n- Issues ready for agent work that haven't been started\n\nThis serves human developers now and becomes a coordinator agent's reporting surface later.\n\n## Multi-Agent Coordination (Future Direction)\n\nCurrent workflow: 3-4 terminals, each with an agent working a different issue through\nthe lifecycle (identify → review → plan → execute → review → merge). The human is the\nstate tracker and dispatcher.\n\nNear-term architecture to consider:\n- GitHub Issues as the task queue (labels like `agent-ready`, `agent-in-progress`)\n- Worktree scripts already enforce isolation per agent\n- Container mode (`agent-run`) as the execution boundary\n- Dashboard as the unified status surface\n\nThis issue should design the target surface area; implementation of individual targets\nhappens in focused issues (#332 for stamp files, #330 for first-run UX, new issues for\ndashboard and orchestration).\n\n## Scope\n\n1. Define the target taxonomy and document which tier each target belongs to\n2. Identify targets to add, remove, merge, or rename\n3. Identify which scripts become internal implementation details vs user-facing\n4. Capture as an update to #332 scope or as input for focused follow-up issues\n\n## Related Issues\n\n- #263 — Simplify scripts and Makefile interface (parent)\n- #325 — ADR-0007: Retain Make with dependency tracking (decision)\n- #332 — Refactor Makefile with stamp-file dependencies (implementation)\n- #330 — Improve first-run initialization UX\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}